        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "If `vim.lsp.completion.enable()` controls only the LSP autotrigger, then wouldn't `vim.lsp.completion.enable(true, ..., { autotrigger = false })` and `vim.lsp.completion.enable(false, ..., { autotrigger = true })` be no-ops? What is the purpose of the `autotrigger` parameter then?\n\nThe `vim.lsp.omnifunc()` calls `vim.lsp.completion.get()`, so the behavior of `.get()` doesn't seem to be influenced by `.enable()`.\n\nThe proposed solution to remove the completion capability is simple and I can accept that as a fix, but it would be great to either remove the redundancy in the API (e.g., deprecate the `autotrigger` parameter), or at least to mention in the docs that `.enable()` only affects LSP autocompletion, and the `.enable()` and `autotrigger` parameters must have the same value.\n\nDid I understand things correctly, or are there uses for `vim.lsp.completion.enable()` besides the autocompletion that I'm missing?",
